RT @undefined: TEXAS FLOODS-Here’s a radar loop from the main event. From Thursday afternoon, July 3rd, through Sunday evening, July 6th. 

A leftover “plume” of tropical moisture from the remnants of Tropical Storm Barry surged north into the state, in combination with elevated moisture from the eastern Pacific from Hurricane Flossie. A shortwave trough emerged from the northwest along with some upper spin from the Gulf, and aided the formation of an MCV over central Texas. 
Starting late Wednesday, a funnel of this tropical moisture began feeding into the Hill Country, and along with the approaching shortwave, fueled the development of the MCV or (mesoscale convective vortex). This “spin” or the MCV, continued to produce widespread tropical downpours and thunderstorms overnight into Friday morning, July 4th. A burst of low-level air and moisture transport, what’s called the LLJ (Low-level jet) also continued to funnel moisture in to this MCV and continued storms overnight. This was where the bulk of the flooding occurred, and filled downstream rivers and tributaries. 

Each subsequent day brought bursts of convectively-driven showers and storms that would further exacerbate the flooding situation, on top of what already fell. This continues today, with more showers and storms forming as we speak. 

#txwx #TexasFloods

RT @undefined: Please pray with us

At approximately 5a CT our beloved friends, the Hammond family were delivering their three children and their friend to a summer camp. 

As their car crossed a bridge in Marble Falls Texas, the bridge collapsed due to rapid flood waters. 

The car plummeted into the rushing current. Their 17 year old daughter, Malaya, managed to open a door to allow everyone to escape. 

Everyone but Malaya made it to land. As I write this she is still missing. 

My family and I are with the Hammond family now. They are the kindest people we’ve ever known— a family rooted deeply in love and God. A family of pure heart and soul. 

Together we are holding strong knowing that Malaya will be rescued. 

This is the first time I’ve made a public request of this nature: 

Please take a moment to pray for Malaya— envision the highest and best possible outcome. Miracles are real. 

Thank you 🙏🏽

Jonathon Lane (Deputy), Nolan (Driver)
October 22, 2024
Marathon, Monroe County, Florida, USA

Facts:
On October 22, 2024, at around 3:30 p.m., Monroe County Sheriff’s Deputy Jonathon Lane stopped a driver, identified only as Nolan, for towing a boat at 10 mph in a 55 mph zone on U.S. 1 near Marathon. 

Nolan, who suffered a traumatic brain injury (TBI), was arrested for felony resisting an officer without violence and driving without a license after allegedly refusing to provide ID and physically resisting. 

Bodycam footage shows Lane escalating the stop, handcuffing Nolan, and lecturing his wife about integrity and law compliance.

The case was dismissed by November 7, 2024, though reasons remain unclear due to sealed records. 

Lane’s April 29, 2023, DUI arrest—when he was found asleep off-duty in a vehicle at a Ramrod Key gas station—surfaced, listed as “confidential” on Monroe County court records, raising coverup allegations. 

Lane was reinstated after his DUI case was dismissed, despite public outcry.

Sheriff Rick Ramsay promised transparency, but the sealed records fueled distrust.

In Qizan al-Najjar, south of Khan Yunis, where life once throbbed, Dr. Hamdi al-Najjar lived within the walls of his home, surrounded by his extended family, who were his entire world.

When the evacuation orders were issued by the occupying army, he did as all fathers do. He carried his children and tried to flee with them to a safe shore. But there was no shore here, no shore of salvation in a sea of ​​fire.

He failed to find a place to shelter him, so he returned to what remained of his world—his small clinic downstairs—in the hope that its walls would protect them, or embrace them in their final moments.

Hamdi took his wife to work at Nasser hospital earlier today. Immediately after returning home to his children, a missile fell. In an instant, nine of his children were killed. Yahya, Rakan, Raslan, Jubran, Eve, Rivan, Sideen, Luqman and Sidra.

Hamdi and his son Adam were injured.

Why? He wasn’t a fighter. He didn’t carry a weapon. He was a doctor, a father, a human being who only dreamed of living.

But in Gaza, there is no time for dreams. People are dying of hunger, lost, and fear. They are dying searching for a life that does not exist and for stability that has no place. In Gaza, even survival has become a miracle.

Dr. Alaa Al-Najjar, a pediatrician at the hospital, is reportedly still there. She hasn’t left her post. She has not stopped working.

(Information from @HCWWatch)

This experience was straight-up incredible—like stepping back into Malcolm’s wild world but with all the love and chaos cranked to 11. Another big thing I am taking away from this experience is how much I truly love being an actor. I never officially felt like that label fit me, but now I wear that label proudly and hope to do so much more of it in the future.
